  "electroenergetics.ponder.transformer_losses.header": "Transformers and energy losses",
  "electroenergetics.ponder.transformer_losses.text_1": "Wires have some resistance, therefore they cause energy losses.",
  "electroenergetics.ponder.transformer_losses.text_2": "299.5V",
  "electroenergetics.ponder.transformer_losses.text_3": "299.4V",
  "electroenergetics.ponder.transformer_losses.text_4": "10A",
  "electroenergetics.ponder.transformer_losses.text_5": "Energy losses are directly proportional to the square of the amperage, and directly proportional to the resistance.",
  "electroenergetics.ponder.transformer_losses.text_6": "Transformers can be used to increase the voltage, therefore decrease the amperage.",
  "electroenergetics.ponder.transformer_losses.text_7": "3.3A",
  "electroenergetics.ponder.transformer_losses.text_8": "For large transmission lines, stepping-up the voltage can greatly decrease energy losses.",
  "electroenergetics.ponder.voltage.header": "What is voltage?",
  "electroenergetics.ponder.voltage.text_1": "Voltage is the measurement of difference of electric potential",
  "electroenergetics.ponder.voltage.text_10": "Connect a device to a voltage difference, and current will start flowing and doing work",
  "electroenergetics.ponder.voltage.text_11": "Never directly connect different voltages!",
  "electroenergetics.ponder.voltage.text_12": "When two different potentials are connected with low resistance, a lot of current starts flowing",
  "electroenergetics.ponder.voltage.text_2": "160V",
  "electroenergetics.ponder.voltage.text_3": "70V",
  "electroenergetics.ponder.voltage.text_4": "-160V",
  "electroenergetics.ponder.voltage.text_5": "Sometimes a voltage value may describe a single point. In that case, it is a value relative to ground, which is always 0V",
  "electroenergetics.ponder.voltage.text_6": "70V",
  "electroenergetics.ponder.voltage.text_7": "230V",
  "electroenergetics.ponder.voltage.text_8": "Notice how the voltage at each connector is -160V and 70V, but the difference is 230V",
  "electroenergetics.ponder.voltage.text_9": "Voltage doesn't mean work. It shows how much work could be done, it's not current or flow, just the possibility of it",
